\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s3 \posx2331 \posy1825 \phpg \pvpg \absh-4216 \absw7341 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \fi434 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx50 \tx484 \tqr \tx7290 Just as it is difficult to decide which options to buy (and which you can afford) when you buy a car, there may seem to be a bewildering array of peripherals to choose for your computer. In this chapter we're going to introduce you to the world of Commodore 128 peripherals, explaining what they are, reviewing what is available in the marketplace, and sug\-\fs25 \f1 \b gesting \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 how to choose which equipment is right for you. We'll then explain just how these peripherals are attached to the Commodore 128. This is not a simple topic. There are so many plugs, openings, ports and connec\-tors of different shapes and sizes on the Commodore 128 that it's necessary to explain which kind of peripheral plugs in where, and why.\par 
