\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s5 \posx2228 \posy4223 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2608 \absw7927 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li638 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx638 \tqr \tx7876 Program cartridges aren't exactly peripherals in the sense a monitor or disk drive is. The cartridge slot (the connector where the cartridges plug in) is already built into the Commodore 128, so there is no major purchase to make to use this peripheral. The sole purpose of program cartridges is to provide a convenient way for software manufacturers to distribute their product. Only the manufacturer can put a program in the cartridge, so you can't use it to store programs of your own, as you can with a cassette or disk drive.\par 
