}\par {\pard \posx3917 \posy1906 \phpg \pvpg \absh-3967 \absw7362 \dxfrtext200 \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 \pard \s2 \posx3917 \posy1906 \phpg \pvpg \absh-3967 \absw7362 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \fi447 \ri68 \sl-261 \tx50 \tx497 \tqr \tx7293 The program cartridge itself is a plastic box about the size of a deck of cards. Some software manufacturers like it because it is almost indes\-tructible, and the program inside can't be conveniently copied. However, cartridges are more expensive to produce than disks, so other manufac\-turers avoid them.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s3 \posx3917 \posy1906 \phpg \pvpg \absh-3967 \absw7362 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li53 \fi447 \ri66 \sl-261 \tx53 \tx500 \tqr \tx7295 There is a considerable variety of commercially produced software available on program cartridges for the Commodore 64, which will also work on the Commodore 128 in the C64 mode. These programs are fairly inexpensive, ranging from around $19 to $40 for games, and up to $100 for more serious programs. It remains to be seen whether software devel\-opers will use this format for programs written specifically for the C128 mode.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s4 \posx3917 \posy1906 \phpg \pvpg \absh-3967 \absw7362 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li59 \fi447 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx59 \tx506 \tqr \tx7311 Something to remember about program cartridges is that you should turn off the power to the computer before plugging in the cartridge. If you don't do this, you run the risk of damaging the computer, or the cartridge.\par 
