\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s3 \posx4075 \posy1589 \phpg \pvpg \absh-10486 \absw7363 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li60 \fi441 \ri65 \sl-261 \tx60 \tx501 \tqr \tx7297 The most important variance between different kinds of modems is that of speed: how fast can the modem send or receive a certain amount of information? A slow modem can take a long time to transmit even a small amount of information; so if you plan to use a modem extensively, a fast one is a good investment.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s4 \posx4075 \posy1589 \phpg \pvpg \absh-10486 \absw7363 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li62 \fi441 \ri61 \sl-261 \tx62 \tx503 \tqr \tx7301 The slowest modems used today are rated at 300 baud. What does baud mean? Very roughly, the baud rate is the number of characters per second the modem can send, divided by 10. Thus, a 300 baud modem can send about 30 characters per second. (This definition isn't exactly right, but it's close enough to give you an idea how fast modems work.)\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s5 \posx4075 \posy1589 \phpg \pvpg \absh-10486 \absw7363 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \fi441 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx50 \tx491 \tqr \tx7312 Commodore sells a variety of modems: the \fs22 \f1 1600 \fs25 \f0 and the \fs22 \f1 1650, \fs25 \f0 which have been around for some time, and the newer \fs22 \f1 1660 \fs25 \f0 and \fs22 \f1 1670, \fs25 \f0 which were introduced with the C128 computer. The first three are 300 baud modems, while the \fs22 \f1 1670, \fs25 \f0 shown in Figure 2\_4, runs at a brisk 1200 baud. While the 300 baud modems range in price from $40 to about $100, the \fs22 \f1 1670 will \fs25 \f0 set you back about $200.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s6 \posx4075 \posy1589 \phpg \pvpg \absh-10486 \absw7363 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li63 \fi441 \ri60 \sl-261 \tx63 \tx504 \tqr \tx7302 In addition to Commodore, there are a wide variety of other modem manufacturers, including Hayes, Human Engineered Software, and An\-chor Automation. Some of these modems are designed to plug directly into the C128, but others will require an adaptor called an RS\_232 inter\-face module, which costs about \fs22 \f1 $50 \fs25 \f0 and can be obtained from several manufacturers, including Commodore and MSD Systems.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s7 \posx4075 \posy1589 \phpg \pvpg \absh-10486 \absw7363 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li51 \fi441 \ri53 \sl-260 \tx51 \tx492 \tqr \tx7309 Besides speed, modems are also distinguished by features such as: Will the modem automatically answer the telephone? Will it automatically dial the phone to make an outgoing call? In the Commodore line, all but the \fs22 \f1 1600 \fs25 \f0 have these autoanswer autodial features. However, the \fs22 \f1 1650 \fs25 \f0 and \fs22 \f1 1660 \fs25 \f0 require special software to use these features. For instance, if you want to dial a number, it is the software that generates the clicks for each digit you dial. In the \fs22 \f1 1670 \fs25 \f0 on the other hand, the modem itself generates the clicks; all the software needs to tell it is what number to dial. The \fs22 \f1 1670 is \fs25 \f0 thus a "smart" modem, which makes it compatible with a wider variety of communications software.\par 
