}\par {\pard \posx2074 \posy1680 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2921 \absw7344 \dxfrtext200 \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 \pard \s2 \posx2074 \posy1680 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2921 \absw7344 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx7293 that each character or byte of information is sent in separate bits, one after the other. Since each byte is composed of eight bits, this way of sending information is theoretically eight times slower than sending each byte all at once, as is done in a parallel connection. However, sending all eight bits at once requires eight separate connectors, so the serial tech\-nique is less expensive.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s3 \posx2074 \posy1680 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2921 \absw7344 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li55 \fi442 \ri53 \sl-261 \tx55 \tx497 \tqr \tx7290 The word bus refers to a kind of data path used in the computer. The bus is really more like a highway than a bus. Data is sent down the bus to a variety of different destinations. Like cities lying along a highway, peripherals can occupy different positions along the bus. Let's look at this arrangement in more detail.\par 
}\sect \sectd \linex0 \linemod0 \sbknone \pghsxn12251 \pgwsxn12240 \marglsxn2024 \margrsxn2750 \pard \sl-261 \tx55 \tx497 \tqr \tx7290 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx2082 \posy4805 \phpg \pvpg \absh-3300 \absw7359 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \b \pard \s4 \posx2082 \posy4805 \phpg \pvpg \absh-3300 \absw7359 \dxfrtext200 \li64 \ri5481 \sl-261 \tx64 \tqr \tx1877 Daisy\_Chaining\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 \pard \s5 \posx2082 \posy4805 \phpg \pvpg \absh-3300 \absw7359 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx50 \tqr \tx7308 An unusual feature of the serial bus connector is that more than one peripheral can be plugged into it. How is this possible? Through a tech\-nique called daisy\_chaining. This means that the first peripheral is plugged directly into the serial bus connector on the back of the computer. Then the second peripheral is plugged, not into the computer, but into the first peripheral. The third peripheral is plugged into the second, and so on. There can be as many as five different peripherals connected to the Com\-modore's serial bus connector. This process is shown in Figure 2\_7.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s6 \posx2082 \posy4805 \phpg \pvpg \absh-3300 \absw7359 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li56 \fi436 \ri69 \sl-259 \tx56 \tx492 \tqr \tx7289 A question that might occur to you is, if all these peripherals are on one cable, how does the computer know which peripheral it's talking to when it sends a message out this connector?\par 
}\pard \sl-259 \tx56 \tx492 \tqr \tx7289 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx2812 \posy8307 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1117 \absw5919 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f2 \i \b \pard \s7 \posx2812 \posy8307 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1117 \absw5919 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx5868 Because the Commodore 128 uses intelligentperipherals that can communicate over a daisy\_chained serial bus, connections are simpler than on other computers, and expanding the system is also easier.\par 
}\pard \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx5868 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx2085 \posy9622 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2530 \absw7347 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \plain \fs25 \f1 \lang1033 \pard \s8 \posx2085 \posy9622 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2530 \absw7347 \dxfrtext200 \li67 \ri4745 \sl-261 \tx67 \tqr \tx2601 Intelligent Peripherals\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 \pard \s9 \posx2085 \posy9622 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2530 \absw7347 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-262 \tx50 \tqr \tx7296 To understand how the serial bus connector works, you should know that the Commodore 128 can make use of a special kind of peripheral device called an intelligent peripheral. In this regard the Commodore is unusual in the computer world. Most computer systems can only use what can be called "dumb" peripherals. The computer tells them exactly what to do, and they report back every little thing that's going on inside them, and can make no decisions without the computer's help. The C64 and C128, on the other hand, can use peripherals that perform complex tasks all by\par 
}\pard \sl-262 \tx50 \tqr \tx7296 \fs24 \f0 \page {\stylesheet {\snext0 Normal;}
